AB  - The treatment of food with ionizing radiation carried out in conditions of good production practice is an efficient and widely applicable method of food processing. However, this procedure is not well accepted by the public and is often accompanied by a negative attitude of consumers regarding the consumption of such food. This is mainly due to their insufficient and incorrect information, as a result of which public opinion is burdened with numerous prejudices and dilemmas. In this paper, an assessment of the views and opinions of a group of respondents was made, in order to determine the level of information and readiness of consumers to buy and consume products treated with ionizing radiation. The research was conducted by surveying 92 respondents, most of them high school professors, employed in two high schools in Bitola (Macedonia). In order to have certain diversity, some of the respondents were students, employees in other school activities and several retirees. All of them belonged to 6 age categories. The survey was conducted with a previously prepared online survey questionnaire, with precisely prepared questions and possible answers. Three aspects were analyzed: (1) level of awareness of the respondents, (2) their previous opinions and attitudes and (3) their readiness to buy and consume a product/food treated with ionizing radiation. Standard descriptive statistical analyses (Microsoft Office Excel 2010, Data Analysis ToolPak and t-test) were used for results processing. Obtained results show insufficient information of the examined persons, wrong beliefs and opinions based on assumptions and personal conclusions made without scientific basis and evidence. In fact, only 8.7% said that they would buy such a product, as opposed to almost 40% who answered negatively. Also, 71.7% do not believe or agree that this type of food is better than food treated with preservatives. 41.3% think that such food is of lower quality, 47.8% believe that with this procedure loses vitamins in food, and even 75% are not sure if this food is carcinogenic. As a consequence, the reluctance of the respondents to accept this modern way of food processing is evident. In this regard, it can be concluded that carefully designed educational programs are needed, which, based on credible results of scientific research, would provide proper information to the public. Introducing the general public to the benefits of this procedure would certainly contribute to changing consumer attitudes. This, combined with quality marketing, would replace all existing dilemmas with safe and correct attitudes towards irradiated food. © 2022, Consulting and Training Center - KEY. All rights reserved.
