AB  - Weight bias greatly impacts the physical, psychological, and social health of individuals with a higher weight. However, current measures of weight bias were developed years, even decades, ago, and have significant conceptual and psychometric limitations. To explore potentially new or understudied dimensions of weight bias, the present research looks at the perceptions of young canadian adults on the different facets of this prejudice using concept mapping. The first goal was to observe and categorize the content of weight bias perceived by the participants. The second goal was to examine the degree to which participants endorsed the items and dimensions generated in the study. Thirty-four participants generated statements describing their perceptions of weight bias in today’s society in the first phase, and 32 different participants categorized these items in the second phase. Fifty-four items were generated and divided by participants into seven weight bias dimensions: (a) Poor eating habits; (b) Poor health/low level of physical activity; (c) Selfneglect; (d) Denial of presumed health risks; (e) Repulsive physical appearance; (f) Negative personality traits, and (g) Limited intellectual capacities. The seven dimensions of weight bias generated in this study add one dimension to existing weight bias measures, Denial, which could be a more recent facet of weight bias. A significant percentage of the bias reported by participants was related to health behaviors and the denial of presumed health risks. These dimensions appear to be more significant than what was described in existing weight bias measures. Findings will be useful in identifying limitations of current measures and in informing the development of new ones. © 2022 American Psychological Association
